---
import PageLayout from '../layouts/PageLayout.astro';
---
<PageLayout
  title="Warranty — Syvidea"
  description="Warranty information for Syvidea's curated partner workstation options."
>
  <article class="section">
    <div class="container-page max-w-3xl prose prose-slate dark:prose-invert">
      <h1>Warranty</h1>
      <p class="lead">
        Warranty terms are provided by the OEM manufacturer. This page summarizes the general approach.
        Final warranty terms for your specific unit are confirmed in your written quote.
      </p>

      <h2>What the warranty covers</h2>
      <p>
        OEM warranty typically covers defects in materials and workmanship under normal use during the
        warranty period. The specific period (commonly 1 or 2 years) and coverage scope depend on the OEM
        and the specific model configuration.
      </p>

      <h2>What is not covered</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>Damage from accidents, drops, spills, or physical impact</li>
        <li>Damage from unauthorized disassembly or modification</li>
        <li>Damage from use outside the documented operating environment</li>
        <li>Normal wear and tear</li>
        <li>Software issues unrelated to hardware defects</li>
        <li>Consumables and accessories (cables, adapters) unless defective on arrival</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>How to make a warranty claim</h2>
      <ol>
        <li>Contact us via the contact form with your order number and a description of the issue.</li>
        <li>We work with the OEM to confirm coverage and next steps.</li>
        <li>Depending on the issue and the OEM process, we may arrange repair, replacement, or return-to-base service.</li>
      </ol>

      <h2>Local support vs. shipping back</h2>
      <p>
        Warranty resolution is handled in coordination with the OEM. For international customers, the OEM's
        regional support path applies. Shipping costs for warranty service are handled per the OEM's policy
        and confirmed at claim time.
      </p>

      <h2>Final terms</h2>
      <p>
        The exact warranty terms for your unit are the terms published by the OEM for the specific
        model and configuration you purchase, as confirmed in your quote. Syvidea helps coordinate
        the claim, but the warranty is ultimately an OEM warranty.
      </p>
    </div>
  </article>
</PageLayout>
